    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The burning sensation during your HIIT sprints is a classic sign of your muscles working at a very high intensity, which is where the real fun—and the real metabolic chaos—begins! You're essentially pushing your muscles to perform a task so fast that they can't get enough oxygen to keep up, which makes them start producing energy through a process that creates lactic acid. To get it out, your body has a few ways, like shunting some of the lactate over to the liver to be recycled, or using it as fuel in other parts of your body. It's a whole biochemical scramble, but think of it like a frantic little cleanup crew in your muscles after a massive, sudden burst of activity.",
